There's nothing actually saying a SGPA couldn't interpret these substructures in light of something like a generalization of variant addition, and in fact, I'd say that doing so is actually the natural way that a SGPA would end up hearing the theme, as being composed of many internal structures as well as being a complete theme that is a canonical sequence anyway, as this enables a greater impression of structural richness and is likely to happen subconsciously anyway. This total sense of structure rising out of all the possibilities enabled by SGP is what I label Variant Construction, which is what this series of articles has been building up to defining. Now, I naturally don't intend to define all the structural possibilities that may result from this, those may be effectively infinite, but I do want to give people a general idea of what this does enable.\par
\par
Variant Construction naturally covers compositional techniques such as "phrase extension" ,  "phrase elision" [4], certain kinds of links between phrases and uses of interpolation to enlarge structure. However, variant construction is primarily an interpretive model, a way of defining and exploring how exactly it is that structures that would otherwise be limited to the expressive power of canonical sequences can be reinterpreted using super grammatical faculties so that these additions and expansions of structural possibility can make sense while enriching the experience of the music. As such, variant construction concerns itself with a totality of structural possibilities that go beyond the techniques mentioned above, and allows the exploration of things like the addition of internal structure to canonical sequences that might affect how their phrasing is interpreted (which someone like Glenn Gould is notably sensitive to). It also affects things like extra motivic grouping, like how patterns between groups (example of Bach C Major prelude from the WTC, use the GTTM grouping analysis from Lerdahl and Jackendoff, 1983) can affect how they relate and form larger groups under grouping structure (like that detailed in the GTTM[3]). Beyond this, it is also concerns with the resolution, or sublation, of ambiguities in the variant structure that may arise from all this (reference Gould video {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1nZTgAGSajA"}}{\fldrslt{\ul\cf1 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1nZTgAGSajA}}}\f0\fs22  and use WTC C minor fugue as example).\par
