But it isn't really sufficient enough the offer a totally satisfying interpretation. None of the subsequent endings feel quite satisfying enough as followups to my ears. But we can think of it in alternate ways.\par
\par
Here is a different way of reinterpreting the sequence of notes. I've shifted the grouping back by one quarter note, and I ask you to listen to the start of the piece again, with this in mind. Here, the groupings match up with the bar lines of the piece as a whole. In fact, you can continue to interpret the piece like this, effectively adding a variant structure consisting of a continuous succession of these half bar groups. The key to understanding why I have called Variant Addition as I have, as opposed to simply calling it variant 'extension' or something similar lies in this potential of creating new interpretations though 'searching' through possible grouping structures . I'm not trying here to specifically label the process of composing music by adding repeating parts in particular ways (though this in naturally relevant to composition), but to name the mental process of mentally building up the music into groups in such a way interpretations more complex than what the canonical sequences of EVP would allow otherwise.\par
\par
Different interpretations of grouping structure will result in different groupings feeling important, but there's nothing actually saying you can't subconsciously experience each of these groupings being a meaningful part of the feel of the phrase structure simultaneously, each of them being a force shaping how you feel and interpret the music. In fact I'd say that in many cases it is ideal to be able to understand multiple grouping structures like this unconsciously and simultaneously (especially in complex frugal works) with the ultimate aim of putting aside such analytical processes and surrendering to the sense of everything flowing smoothly, working together at the same time while you are barely aware of any conscious attempt to analyse anything. In this flow state, explicit awareness of division into grouping structure will feel unnatural.\par
\par
\par
\par
The EVA-SGN understanding of how sequences of canonical sequences flow within a given single voice is generally similar to continuously right embedded structure in language, with each theme running its course then, depending on how solidly it ends in a cadence (determined by the 'strength' of the note and how it resolved relative to the global key that has been established), continuing on through the next theme instance (whether it be a variation of the same theme or other material that follows melodically). It should be noted though that the size of a meaningful cadence is strictly limited in SGPNs. Large scale (arbitrarily large scale?) center embedded structures (including those that result in such big cadences being permissible at their end) however, are made possible by Variant Construction. Through this, SGP also allows subsections effectively resolving into a different key to be embedded in larger structures, and all kinds of basically arbitrary musical structure to be built up using these techniques.\par
