If we want to look at what can be achieved with variant construction and what this piece does with it's structure that demands the listener has SGP in order to understand it, we could do worse that to look at the end of the first line (the fourth bar) here. Look at what is happening with the melody. We can see that the first bar starts with a middle G, then the melody progresses through to the second bar to an A, just before falling firmly on a D, the implicit dominant of the piece. The same sort of sequence happens within the third bar as well. But it's in the forth bar that something relatively strange happens. The whole bar parallels the previous, there's a sense in which, for its first three quarters at least, it is a canonical transformation of bar three. We still start with a middle G, and continue through a similar sequence as the previous bar, only with additional embellishments (the extra G and A following the D eighth notes). But instead of simple ending with an A to D quaver sequence with the final two notes, that gets shoved into two sixteenth notes that constitute the penultimate 8th of the bar (where the top red arrow falls) rather than the whole third quarter, effectively ending the theme earlier than it feels like it should have, leaving the final eighth for the use of new material. This produces the sense that the theme has finished too quickly to properly resolve, introducing the start of a new thematic section at the point where the motif feels like it ought to completed instead.\par
\par
But hang on, isn't the second last note still a D, falling in the same place in the only an octave higher? And couldn't this mean that there's a sense in which the final four notes are an embellishment of the A to D step in the previous bar? Try listening to the piece again and with this interpretation in mind. It's unnatural and results in a complete lack of resolution doesn't it? But on the whole doesn't this feel similar to what happened in the Montiverdi piece before, where the end of one section is forced to become the beginning of another, in a way that demands that your mind find some way to resolve it, but is otherwise awkward and unsatisfying if you can't? I know I was completely unable to resolve this when I lacked SGP. But now, for me, there's a sense that it acts as a structural hinge that links together different parts by making you interpret them as extensions of other material.\par
\par
We only have to look further into the piece to see what the melodic structure could have done in contrast. In fact, this form of it occurs in the bass only a short time after. Here, the part that is equivalent to the 'hinge' in the section where the material is first introduced is played out in they way you would expect it to be played in order to give it a firm resolution. The marked sections are able to parallel each other as (modified through embellishment) canonical material and resolve in parallel fashion, before continuing on into a cadential sequence resolving to D (though I guess this would be a half-cadence in this instance [1]).\par
\par
We can see that Bach could have done something along these lines in the first place, but chose not to. Instead, different sequences are linked, differently in each instance, thought sometimes in similar ways, as the piece plays out. Not all of these links occur with the same 'hinge' structure, there are other types of links (extending phrases), some simpler in that they produce less ambiguity, along with other, more complex forms of parallelism (allowing the feeling of response) based on combinations of thematic (canonical transform based) parallels and grouping (hierarchical block structure).\par
