We only have to look further into the piece to see what the melodic structure could have done in contrast. In fact, this form of it occurs in the bass only a short time after. Here, the part that is equivalent to the 'hinge' in the section where the material is first introduced is played out in they way you would expect it to be played in order to give it a firm resolution. The marked sections&nbsp;are able to parallel each other as (modified through embellishment) canonical material and resolve in parallel fashion, before continuing on into a cadential sequence resolving to D (though I guess this would be a <i>half-cadence</i>&nbsp;in this instance&nbsp;<a href="https://www.google.com.au/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0ahUKEwi-oJTL3OLTAhWFerwKHSk5D-gQFggzMAE&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.music.mcgill.ca%2F~caplin%2Fcaplin-classical-cadence.pdf&amp;usg=AFQjCNFVHDsEigNII87GO8DVbvDiZCDPhw&amp;sig2=tnGf58hV8leizSELEHHHCQ" target="_blank">[1]</a>).<br />\par
<div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">\par
<a href="https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-tfUUWsX-bJs/WQ599y7nLmI/AAAAAAAAAIQ/1Rf-lXX4E3w2-hVDYMf_neHBrgFGddLCACLcB/s1600/Bach_Little_bass.png" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"><img border="0" src="https://4.bp.blogspot.com/-tfUUWsX-bJs/WQ599y7nLmI/AAAAAAAAAIQ/1Rf-lXX4E3w2-hVDYMf_neHBrgFGddLCACLcB/s1600/Bach_Little_bass.png" /></a></div>\par
We can see that Bach could have done something along these lines in the first place, but chose not to. Instead, different sequences are linked, differently in each instance, thought sometimes in similar ways, as the piece plays out. Not all of these links occur with the same 'hinge' structure, there are other types of links (<span style="color: blue;">extending phrases</span>), some simpler in that they produce less ambiguity, along with other, more complex forms of parallelism (<b>allowing the feeling of response</b>) based on combinations of thematic (canonical transform based) parallels and grouping (hierarchical block structure).<br />\par
<br />\par
<br />\par
---<br />\par
<br />\par
The EVA-SGN understanding of how sequences of canonical themes flow within a given single voice is generally similar to continuously right embedded structure in language, with each theme running its course then, depending on how solidly it ends in a cadence (determined by the 'strength' of the note and how it resolved relative to the global key that has been established in the listener's mind), continuing on through the next theme instance (whether it be a variation of the same theme or other material that follows melodically). It should be noted though that the size of a meaningful cadence is strictly limited in SGPNs. Large scale (arbitrarily large scale?) center embedded structures (including those that result in such big cadences being permissible at their end) however, are made possible by Variant Construction. Through this, SGP also allows subsections effectively resolving into a different key to be embedded in larger structures, and all kinds of basically arbitrary musical structure to be built up using these techniques.<br />\par
<br />\par
<span style="color: #cc0000;">When the time comes to end a piece, the ending is often extended beyond what is necessary to simply complete that section's phrase, as if simply putting a single full stop on the end of a theme and letting it come to rest. In certain styles of music, it's common to extend and effectively develop the ending itself too, expanding it similarly to how phrases might be expended themselves in the development section of a piece.</span><br />\par
<span style="color: #cc0000;"><br /></span>\par
<span style="color: #cc0000;"><a href="https://youtu.be/xAQFJ1YpFaI?t=12m40s">https://youtu.be/xAQFJ1YpFaI?t=12m40s</a></span><br />\par
<br />\par
When this occurs, variant addition enables this kind of post-candential expansion.<br />\par
